# General Software Development Principles

## SOLID

| Principle | Rule |
|---|---|
| **SRP** | One module/function = one reason to change. If the name needs "and", split it. |
| **OCP** | Extend via composition and new modules — don't edit working code to add behavior. |
| **LSP** | Replacements must honor the same interface/behavior contract. |
| **ISP** | Small, focused interfaces — no "god" classes or mega-interfaces. |
| **DIP** | Depend on abstractions (interfaces, types), not concrete implementations. |

## Core Acronyms

- **DRY** — Centralize shared logic. Duplication breeds bugs.
- **KISS** — Simplest design that works. No unnecessary abstractions.
- **YAGNI** — Don't build it until you need it.

## Clean Code

- Names reveal intent: `getUserById`, `isValidEmail`, `StockPriceChart`
- Booleans: `is`, `has`, `should` prefix
- Functions: verb + noun (`fetchUser`, `validateEmail`)
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Functions are small, single-purpose, 3 or fewer params (use options object beyond that)
- Minimal nesting — use early returns and guard clauses
- Comments explain **why**, not **what**. Never commit commented-out code.
- Handle errors at a sensible layer; never swallow silently; use typed errors

## Design Patterns

- **Composition over inheritance** — build from small parts
- **Strategy / Factory** — choose behavior via config, not big `if/else` chains
- **Observer / Pub-Sub** — for decoupled event-driven updates

## Testing

- **Pyramid**: many unit → fewer integration → few E2E
- Test behavior and outcomes, not implementation details
- Deterministic: mock time, randomness, I/O
- No network calls in unit tests

## Security

- Validate and sanitize all input
- Parameterized queries for data layers
- Secure auth (tokens, HTTPS, HttpOnly cookies)
- Principle of least privilege

## Performance

- Measure before optimizing — profiler, Lighthouse, bundle analysis
- Cache when appropriate (HTTP, memoization, query caching)
- Pagination and virtualization for large data sets
- Lazy loading for routes and heavy modules

## Version Control

- One logical change per commit
- Message: `type(scope): summary` — types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `test`, `docs`, `chore`
- Short-lived branches; merge/rebase often; delete after merge

## Project Structure

- Group by feature: `features/stocks/`, `features/portfolio/`
- Shared code in top-level `components/`, `services/`, `utils/`, `models/`
- One main class/component per file
- Tests co-located next to the code they test
